data.content:
## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions change overload resolution. `array.Contains(num)` now binds to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains`** (span-based) instead of **`Enumerable.Contains`**. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so compilation succeeds but **execution throws** (`NotSupportedException` or `InvalidOperationException`).

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or use `.AsEnumerable()` to force the LINQ overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects `array.Reverse()` resolving to the in-place `Span` version â€” use `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `.AsEnumerable().Reverse()` in those cases too.
